> For your Quick Dish of the week we didn't need to make things complicated - the
> ingredients spoke for themselves. If you've never much liked eating the skin on
> salmon give it a second chance as this cooking method makes it crispy and
> delicious!

Boil a #pot{} of water with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the potatoes. Wash the @new potatoes{about 500%g} and chop them into quarters. Put the potatoes in the boiling water for around ~{10-12%mins} or until just soft enough to eat. Drain and keep to the side.

Meanwhile, chop @fresh dill{1%tbsp}(chopped) and keep to the side. Season the @salmon fillet{2} on both sides with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch} and pre-heat your #grill{} to high.

Pre-heat a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat with @olive oil{1%tbsp}. Once the pan is hot lay in the salmon skin side down. Leave it to cook for around ~{4%mins} and resist the urge to move the fish, as it may stick to the pan.

Remove the frying pan from the heat and put under the grill for around ~{5%mins} with the handle facing outwards.

After 5 mins take the frying pan from under the grill using a #tea towel{} or #oven glove{} to touch the hot handle. Place the pan back on the hob and add @butter{1%tsp}.

> If you don't have butter use olive oil instead.

Once the butter has melted and starts to foam squeeze in the juice of @lemon{1/3} and spoon the juices over the salmon, then remove it to a #plate{}.

Add another couple of tsp of @butter{2%tsp} to the pan and cook until it foams and goes slightly brown (they call this 'beurre noisette', but you can call it foamy butter). Take the frying pan off the heat, scatter in the dill and the @capers{1} and season with a bit of @salt{} and @black pepper{}.

Toss together the @wild rocket{1/2%bunch} and new potatoes with a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Grate over a bit of @lemon zest{bit} for a burst of citrus flavour. Portion out the potatoes, place the salmon on top and pour over a bit of the dill and caper sauce.